
1. Train / Validation / Test Split

Description:
The dataset is divided into three parts: training data used to train the machine learning model, validation data used to tune model parameters,
and test data used to evaluate the final performance.
In financial systems this split should be time-based rather than random to avoid future information leaking into the training data.
This method helps determine whether the model can generalize to unseen market conditions.

2. Walk-Forward Validation

Description:
Walk-forward validation evaluates the model using a rolling time window. The model is trained on historical data and then tested on the next time period. 
The window then moves forward and the process repeats.This method closely simulates real-world trading conditions and prevents look-ahead bias. 
It is commonly used in financial machine learning because markets evolve over time.

3. Backtesting

Description:
Backtesting simulates how the model would have performed if it had been used for trading in the past. Predictions generated by the model are converted into trading 
signals (buy, sell, or hold), and the resulting portfolio performance is calculated using historical market data.
Key metrics such as total return, Sharpe ratio, win rate, and maximum drawdown are used to evaluate the effectiveness of the strategy

4. Sentiment Model Validation

Description:
Since the system uses sentiment analysis, the sentiment component should be evaluated independently.
A labeled dataset of financial news or social media posts can be used to compare the predicted sentiment (positive, negative, neutral) with the true labels.
Performance can be measured using metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, F1 score, and confusion matrices

5. Stress Testing

Description:
Stress testing evaluates how the model performs during extreme market conditions such as financial crises, rapid market crashes, or periods of high volatility. 
Historical periods such as the 2008 financial crisis or the 2020 COVID-19 crash can be used to observe whether the model remains stable or produces excessive losses.
